<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What is a Content-Security-Policy header?", answer: "A Content-Security-Policy (CSP) header is an HTTP response header that tells the browser which sources of content are allowed to load on a page. By specifying approved origins for scripts, styles, images, fonts, and other resources, CSP prevents cross-site scripting (XSS), clickjacking, and other code injection attacks. The browser enforces the policy by blocking any resource that does not match the declared sources." },
  { question: "What does default-src control?", answer: "The default-src directive acts as a fallback for any fetch directive that is not explicitly set. If you define default-src 'self' and do not set a separate script-src, the browser will only allow scripts from your own origin. Once you add a specific directive like script-src, it overrides default-src for that resource type. Setting default-src 'none' and then adding individual directives is considered the most restrictive and secure approach." },
  { question: "When should I use unsafe-inline or unsafe-eval?", answer: "Avoid using 'unsafe-inline' and 'unsafe-eval' whenever possible because they weaken CSP by allowing inline scripts and dynamic code evaluation, which are the primary vectors for XSS attacks. If your application relies on inline scripts, migrate to nonce-based or hash-based CSP instead. Use 'unsafe-inline' only as a temporary measure during migration, and set a clear timeline to remove it." },
  { question: "What is the difference between the HTTP header and the meta tag?", answer: "Both deliver the same policy, but the HTTP header is set by the server and applies before the page renders. The meta tag is embedded in the HTML and parsed by the browser when it reaches that tag. The HTTP header supports all directives including frame-ancestors and report-uri, while the meta tag does not support frame-ancestors, report-uri, or sandbox. For full protection, use the HTTP header." },
  { question: "How do I test my CSP without breaking my site?", answer: "Use the Content-Security-Policy-Report-Only header instead of Content-Security-Policy. This tells the browser to report violations without actually blocking anything. Set a report-uri endpoint to collect violation reports and review them before switching to enforcement mode. This lets you identify all resources that would be blocked and adjust your policy before it goes live." }
]) %>

